The data shows that people use Instagram, LinkedIn, and Snapchat the most, with Instagram being the most popular. People also watch YouTube and use other online streaming services like Netflix. Most people seem to feel good or okay in terms of mood and productivity. However, some struggle with falling asleep, and many feel tired when they wake up in the morning. Overall, the data suggests that while social media is popular, it might be affecting people’s sleep and energy levels.

# Lets plot correlation between columns
cor.plot(dataset)

Insights: Users who spend more time on Instagram tend to also use Snapchat and WhatsApp/WeChat extensively. People who have difficulty waking up feeling tired in the morning also tend to experience trouble falling asleep. Those who struggle to fall asleep are more likely to spend significant time on Instagram and Snapchat. Users who report feeling tired upon waking up in the morning have an opposite correlation with LinkedIn and YouTube, implying that those who use LinkedIn and YouTube less tend to feel more tired in the morning.

The variance explained by each principal component, with PC1 explaining the highest variance. Variable loadings on each component, indicating their contribution to the component’s variation. Interpretation suggests PC1 represents overall social media usage, PC2 reflects professional networking, and so on. PCA helps simplify the dataset’s structure, aiding in dimensionality reduction and identifying underlying patterns in the data.
